{
  "answer": "Iqbal's takhallus (pen name), meaning \"good fortune\" or prosperity, routinely appears in the *maqṭaʿ*—the signature closing couplet(s)—of his Urdu ghazals in *Bang-e-Dara*. It is typically invoked via self-address (\"ae Iqbal\" or \"O Iqbal\" in translation), marking the poet's voice in a moment of introspection, irony, or aspiration. This convention aligns with classical Urdu/Persian *ghazal* form, where the takhallus authenticates authorship while weaving into the poem's thematic closure.[^1][^2][^3]\n\nAs a trope, the name enables self-dialogue that contrasts its auspicious connotation with existential pain, spiritual longing, or critique. For instance:\n- It juxtaposes \"good fortune\" against a \"broken heart's... cries of pain,\" underscoring ironic appeal amid suffering.[^1]\n- It positions the poet among his own \"critics,\" using fortune's self-reference for humble self-scrutiny.[^2]\n- It invokes fortune in a plea for pilgrimage, aspiring to abase prosperity into \"dust upon the road to Hejaz.\"[^3]\n\nThis name-as-trope thus heightens philosophical tension: prosperity (*Iqbal*) confronts transience, critique, and divine yearning, embodying the poet's signature motif of self-realization through adversity.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 2 (\"Anokhi waza hai, saare zamane se nirale hain\"), [translation/#p-0118fb](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/02-anokhi-waza-hai-saare-zamane-se-nirale-hain/translation/#p-0118fb).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 4 (\"Jinhein main dhoondta tha aasmanon mein zameenon mein\"), [translation/#p-808707](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/04-jinhein-main-dhoondta-tha-aasmanon-mein-zameenon-m/translation/#p-808707).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 6 (\"Kushaada dast-e-karam jab woh beniyaaz kare\"), [translation/#p-6ee0b9](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/06-kushaada-dast-e-karam-jab-woh-beniyaaz-kare/translation/#p-6ee0b9).",
